Bring a large #pot of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce. Trim and
thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince or
grate @garlic{2%cloves}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a medium pot over high heat. Add
@coleslaw mix{4%ounce} and cook, stirring constantly, until lightly charred,
~{1-2%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate.

Add @ground pork{10%ounce}; cook, breaking up meat with a #spatula, until
browned and cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Once pork is done, add @Szechuan paste{2%tablespoon} and @peanut butter{1.15%ounce};
cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly browned and combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @pork ramen stock concentrate{1}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and
2 1/2 cups water (4 1/2 cups for 4 servings). Bring to a boil, then reduce heat
to low. Cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly thickened, ~{2-4%minutes}.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if necessary.

Once salted water is boiling, add half the @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce}
(all for 4 servings) to #pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente,
~{5-7%minutes}.

Drain noodles; rinse under cold water for ~{30%seconds}.

Divide noodles between large #soup bowls{}. Pour broth over noodles and top with
charred cabbage. Garnish with scallion greens, remaining @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon},
and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste. Serve.

> As much fun to say as they are to eat, dan dan noodles are a great classic of Szechuan cuisine. Here, our chefs make it easy for you to experience the soul-stirring noodle bowl at home. Start with a richly layered broth of zingy, spicy, Szechuan paste, peanut butter, and sesame seeds. Add savory ground pork, charred cabbage, and of course the noodles. Garnish with more sesame seeds and scallion greens for a slurp-tastic meal!